# 17. Compilation Model

---

## 17.1 Overview

Compilation translates Tyr source code into one or more backend representations.

Compilation shall preserve the observable semantics defined by this specification.

---

## 17.2 Translation Units

Each Tyr source file represents a translation unit.

Compiler directives are processed before lexical analysis.

---

## 17.3 Compilation Stages

A conforming implementation typically performs the following stages.

1. Compiler Directive Processing
2. Lexical Analysis
3. Parsing
4. Semantic Analysis
5. Elaboration
6. Hardware Graph Construction
7. Optimization
8. Backend Generation

Alternative implementations are permitted provided language semantics remain unchanged.

---

## 17.4 Diagnostics

Compilation diagnostics should identify:

- source location
- diagnostic severity
- explanatory message

Additional diagnostic information is implementation-defined.

---

## 17.5 Optimization

Implementations may perform arbitrary optimizations.

Optimizations shall not modify observable hardware behaviour.

---

## 17.6 Elaboration

Elaboration constructs the complete hardware design hierarchy.

Module instantiation occurs during elaboration.

---

## 17.7 Hardware Graph

After semantic analysis, implementations should construct an internal hardware representation.

The structure of this representation is implementation-defined.

---

## 17.8 Output

Implementations may generate:

- Verilog
- VHDL
- simulation models
- synthesis netlists
- implementation-specific targets

The output format does not alter language semantics.
